1
00:00:00,580 --> 00:00:01,780
Anywhere is fine.

2
00:00:01,860 --> 00:00:04,260
Please tell me about
any places associated with Hasegawa-san.

3
00:00:04,670 --> 00:00:07,370
We really know so little
about Hasegawa-san.

4
00:00:08,020 --> 00:00:10,460
So first, we need to make
an effort to get to know him.

5
00:00:11,040 --> 00:00:12,670
By "we," do you mean... including me?

6
00:00:13,040 --> 00:00:14,510
That I don't know Itsuki?

7
00:00:14,740 --> 00:00:15,740
Yes.

8
00:00:16,210 --> 00:00:17,410
You two have drifted apart.

9
00:00:18,060 --> 00:00:20,350
Could it be because
Kasuga-san, just like me,

10
00:00:20,350 --> 00:00:22,820
never truly tried to understand
Hasegawa-san?

11
00:00:22,890 --> 00:00:24,750
What makes you say that?

12
00:00:26,020 --> 00:00:27,620
The night Hasegawa-san left,

13
00:00:28,060 --> 00:00:31,090
both Kasuga-san and I only worried
about what would happen to the documentary.

14
00:00:32,560 --> 00:00:36,060
Yamada was the only one
who actually worried about Hasegawa-san.

15
00:00:36,400 --> 00:00:37,400
Huh?

16
00:00:38,730 --> 00:00:40,600
Was that a compliment?

17
00:00:40,600 --> 00:00:42,040
Shiho-san, were you praising...

18
00:00:44,540 --> 00:00:48,440
I used to only see Hasegawa-san
as Kasuga-san's partner,

19
00:00:48,480 --> 00:00:50,500
and I never thought about him
as his own independent person.

20
00:00:51,860 --> 00:00:53,950
I even thought he was a nuisance.

21
00:00:55,200 --> 00:00:58,420
I'd think, "Kasuga-san is so cooperative,
so why is he being so difficult?"

22
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:04,380
But from now on, I want to get to know
Hasegawa Itsuki as an individual.

23
00:01:06,100 --> 00:01:09,560
It might be too late,
but I still want to try.

24
00:01:10,200 --> 00:01:11,530
So please, help me.

25
00:01:15,300 --> 00:01:19,640
But when it comes to places he's connected to,
I really can't think of any.

26
00:01:20,220 --> 00:01:22,510
I only know he cut ties with his parents.

27
00:01:23,240 --> 00:01:26,060
Just like Kayano-san said,
I really know nothing about him...

28
00:01:26,060 --> 00:01:27,060
Um...

29
00:01:27,600 --> 00:01:29,480
Could this be a clue?

30
00:01:31,350 --> 00:01:32,420
This is...

31
00:01:32,420 --> 00:01:34,160
Doesn't this look like
Itsuki-san's account?

32
00:01:34,160 --> 00:01:35,560
Huh? Hasegawa-san's?

33
00:01:35,560 --> 00:01:37,590
Look at this photo.

34
00:01:38,230 --> 00:01:38,990
It really is.

35
00:01:39,030 --> 00:01:40,030
Wait, how did you find this?

36
00:01:40,030 --> 00:01:42,870
Well, I couldn't think of any places
associated with Itsuki-san either.

37
00:01:42,900 --> 00:01:45,000
I only knew the mobile game he plays.

38
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:47,940
But when I searched his username,
I found this.

39
00:01:48,220 --> 00:01:50,010
This is Enoshima, right?

40
00:01:50,420 --> 00:01:54,580
Oh, we went there together
for his birthday last year...

41
00:01:57,340 --> 00:01:59,040
I had no idea...

42
00:01:59,650 --> 00:02:02,780
I thought he didn't use
social media.

43
00:02:02,920 --> 00:02:04,890
Could this be a lead?

44
00:02:06,820 --> 00:02:07,690
Yeah.

45
00:02:16,140 --> 00:02:17,140
Come to think of it,

46
00:02:17,460 --> 00:02:19,900
you always walked ahead, and I followed behind, right?

47
00:02:20,140 --> 00:02:21,740
No, that's not true.

48
00:02:22,280 --> 00:02:24,320
Before I knew it,
you were always ahead of me.

49
00:02:24,710 --> 00:02:25,910
No, I wasn't.

50
00:02:27,060 --> 00:02:30,550
So... that's how it was.

51
00:02:37,320 --> 00:02:38,520
Um...

52
00:02:39,320 --> 00:02:40,490
For these interviews...

53
00:02:41,960 --> 00:02:43,590
Can I come along?

54
00:03:23,900 --> 00:03:30,900
"The boy and I Who Will Break Up in 100 Days"
(Episode 5)

55
00:03:33,640 --> 00:03:35,300
(Day 70)
I think it was about six months ago.

56
00:03:35,420 --> 00:03:37,900
One day, the other volunteers
cancelled at the last minute.

57
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:41,980
I was at a loss, but Itsuki
happened to pass by and spoke to me.

58
00:03:44,200 --> 00:03:46,630
- What are they doing?
- They're doing an interview.

59
00:03:46,720 --> 00:03:48,360
They want to know about Itsuki's past.

60
00:03:49,420 --> 00:03:51,960
He complains a lot, though.

61
00:03:51,980 --> 00:03:56,300
But he helps out at the soup kitchen
and plays with the kids.

62
00:03:56,330 --> 00:03:57,430
He's been a huge help.

63
00:03:57,540 --> 00:03:59,400
(Day 71)
Oh, Itsuki?

64
00:03:59,740 --> 00:04:01,560
He often came to buy croquettes.

65
00:04:01,560 --> 00:04:03,100
I see.

66
00:04:03,100 --> 00:04:04,120
When was it again?

67
00:04:04,120 --> 00:04:05,840
He even asked me for the recipe.

68
00:04:06,340 --> 00:04:08,410
He said his partner loved fried food,

69
00:04:08,410 --> 00:04:11,650
but his always turned out too greasy.

70
00:04:11,700 --> 00:04:14,560
By the way, when was that?

71
00:04:14,560 --> 00:04:17,350
Around the beginning of this year.

72
00:04:17,640 --> 00:04:19,870
Are you Itsuki's partner?

73
00:04:19,960 --> 00:04:21,590
Oh, no, I'm not.

74
00:04:21,590 --> 00:04:22,890
We'll be on our way then.

75
00:04:22,930 --> 00:04:25,390
If it was the beginning of this year...

76
00:04:26,700 --> 00:04:28,030
That was after we broke up.

77
00:04:29,680 --> 00:04:31,030
Which one is better?

78
00:04:31,270 --> 00:04:32,230
Huh?

79
00:04:32,230 --> 00:04:35,370
Itsuki-san's croquettes
compared to this... Be honest.

80
00:04:41,010 --> 00:04:42,620
Probably Itsuki's...

81
00:04:44,420 --> 00:04:45,650
croquettes.

82
00:04:46,200 --> 00:04:47,940
Must be nice.

83
00:04:50,120 --> 00:04:51,680
Hello, I'm the one
who called earlier.

84
00:04:51,680 --> 00:04:52,350
Are you Kayano-san?

85
00:04:52,350 --> 00:04:53,720
- Yes.
- Please, come in.

86
00:04:55,080 --> 00:04:56,900
I had him do a cooking trial,

87
00:04:56,940 --> 00:04:58,260
and it was absolutely delicious.

88
00:04:58,400 --> 00:05:00,480
So I hired him on the spot.

89
00:05:01,680 --> 00:05:04,170
He really got along with everyone.

90
00:05:04,170 --> 00:05:07,640
With his friendly personality
and amazing cooking skills,

91
00:05:07,640 --> 00:05:11,400
he brought in a lot of regular customers.

92
00:05:12,540 --> 00:05:16,040
Um... do you know why he quit?

93
00:05:17,680 --> 00:05:18,680
Well,

94
00:05:19,210 --> 00:05:20,720
I'm not really sure.

95
00:05:21,920 --> 00:05:22,920
Um...

96
00:05:23,360 --> 00:05:27,000
Is there any staff member
who was close to Itsuki?

97
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:28,790
Yes. Should I go get her?

98
00:05:29,680 --> 00:05:30,730
Yes, please.

99
00:05:32,660 --> 00:05:33,800
Sorry for speaking out of turn.

100
00:05:33,800 --> 00:05:34,800
Oh, not at all.

101
00:05:36,520 --> 00:05:40,270
By the way, Kasuga-san,
how do you feel after these interviews?

102
00:05:42,270 --> 00:05:43,270
Honestly,

103
00:05:44,010 --> 00:05:46,380
it feels like I'm hearing
about a complete stranger.

104
00:05:48,180 --> 00:05:49,180
I feel the same way.

105
00:05:50,020 --> 00:05:51,110
Really?

106
00:05:52,750 --> 00:05:53,750
Huh?

107
00:05:54,750 --> 00:05:57,420
Hasegawa-san is very social,

108
00:05:58,300 --> 00:06:00,020
and he's an amazing cook.

109
00:06:01,280 --> 00:06:04,030
I don't think any of this is surprising.

110
00:06:10,030 --> 00:06:11,230
Long time no see.

111
00:06:11,590 --> 00:06:14,470
We talked briefly
the last time you came by, right?

112
00:06:14,470 --> 00:06:15,590
Oh, yes.

113
00:06:15,670 --> 00:06:16,710
I remember.

114
00:06:22,490 --> 00:06:23,490
Actually, I...

115
00:06:25,310 --> 00:06:29,380
know the real reason
why Hasegawa-san quit.

116
00:06:30,370 --> 00:06:31,390
What?

117
00:06:33,570 --> 00:06:37,360
It was a slow day at the restaurant,

118
00:06:38,410 --> 00:06:39,410
so

119
00:06:40,050 --> 00:06:44,810
I went to clean the smoking area
by the back door.

120
00:06:49,070 --> 00:06:50,070
And then,

121
00:06:53,850 --> 00:06:56,480
I saw Hasegawa-san standing there.

122
00:07:05,590 --> 00:07:10,230
He was looking at the customers
in the smoking area.

123
00:07:10,390 --> 00:07:11,970
Didn't you notice?

124
00:07:11,970 --> 00:07:14,160
The way they look at each other,
they're definitely dating.

125
00:07:14,200 --> 00:07:16,060
That man was Kasuga-san's boss.

126
00:07:18,070 --> 00:07:19,200
Oh...

127
00:07:19,670 --> 00:07:22,470
By the way, what's that subordinate's name?

128
00:07:22,770 --> 00:07:24,210
Huh? Oh, Kasuga?

129
00:07:24,210 --> 00:07:26,380
Yeah, he's one of "them" too, right?

130
00:07:26,410 --> 00:07:28,180
I guess so.

131
00:07:28,180 --> 00:07:29,470
What?

132
00:07:29,470 --> 00:07:31,080
If he confessed to you,
would you let him hit on you?

133
00:07:31,080 --> 00:07:32,710
No way in hell.

134
00:07:33,150 --> 00:07:34,280
Why not?

135
00:07:34,530 --> 00:07:36,290
Doesn't your company care about diversity?

136
00:07:36,570 --> 00:07:37,570
Just take one for the team.

137
00:07:38,290 --> 00:07:39,190
I guess...

138
00:07:39,190 --> 00:07:41,990
Hiring gays is an easy way
to look progressive.

139
00:07:41,990 --> 00:07:43,630
It's great for PR.

140
00:07:43,630 --> 00:07:44,590
That's harsh.

141
00:07:44,590 --> 00:07:46,090
Oh, Hasegawa-san...

142
00:07:46,760 --> 00:07:47,530
What?

143
00:07:47,860 --> 00:07:49,100
Hasegawa-san!

144
00:07:49,230 --> 00:07:53,040
- Hasegawa-san, stop!
- Hey, stop it!

145
00:07:54,900 --> 00:07:56,110
Are you okay?

146
00:07:56,110 --> 00:08:00,780
At the end of the shift,
Hasegawa-san told me he was quitting.

147
00:08:02,250 --> 00:08:05,810
He begged me not to tell
anyone what happened.

148
00:08:08,990 --> 00:08:13,390
Even though he hit a customer,

149
00:08:18,650 --> 00:08:20,210
isn't it unfair?

150
00:08:21,130 --> 00:08:25,100
Why does Hasegawa-san
have to be the one to suffer?

151
00:08:26,530 --> 00:08:27,700
Because...

152
00:08:29,070 --> 00:08:30,070
Hasegawa-san...

153
00:08:47,160 --> 00:08:48,160
Yeah.

154
00:08:50,160 --> 00:08:54,030
So you're saying
you want to make two versions?

155
00:08:54,350 --> 00:08:55,330
Yes.

156
00:08:55,850 --> 00:08:59,840
Version A will be the original plan,
showing a same-sex couple's daily life

157
00:08:59,870 --> 00:09:01,840
to promote public understanding.

158
00:09:01,950 --> 00:09:02,990
That's Plan A.

159
00:09:03,970 --> 00:09:08,010
Version B will deviate from the plan
and show what actually happened,

160
00:09:08,010 --> 00:09:09,470
within broadcast limits.

161
00:09:09,650 --> 00:09:11,210
That's Plan B.

162
00:09:11,680 --> 00:09:15,520
We'll submit both and let
the producer make the final call.

163
00:09:16,590 --> 00:09:17,590
I see.

164
00:09:18,010 --> 00:09:22,930
That way, you don't compromise on
the message or the deadline.

165
00:09:23,130 --> 00:09:24,130
Yes.

166
00:09:24,550 --> 00:09:27,660
But if the network thinks
we're taking unnecessary risks,

167
00:09:27,700 --> 00:09:30,830
it might hurt our relationship with them.

168
00:09:31,390 --> 00:09:34,130
So, if you think
we should only submit Plan A...

169
00:09:34,130 --> 00:09:35,800
We could just submit Plan B.

170
00:09:37,210 --> 00:09:38,240
What?

171
00:09:38,790 --> 00:09:41,980
Taking the heat is my job.

172
00:09:43,810 --> 00:09:46,750
Besides, I've caused you
a lot of trouble in the past, Shiho.

173
00:09:47,250 --> 00:09:49,520
Consider this my way of making amends.

174
00:09:49,890 --> 00:09:51,190
You can lean on me.

175
00:09:56,810 --> 00:09:58,290
Thank you.

176
00:10:00,500 --> 00:10:01,500
But

177
00:10:02,130 --> 00:10:05,770
to take responsibility on my end,
please let me make both versions.

178
00:10:05,800 --> 00:10:07,240
Alright, I understand.

179
00:10:08,300 --> 00:10:09,500
Good luck.

180
00:10:09,910 --> 00:10:12,310
Thank you so much.

181
00:10:24,950 --> 00:10:26,260
Whoa! You scared me!

182
00:10:28,650 --> 00:10:29,850
How did you know I was here?

183
00:10:30,650 --> 00:10:31,790
What?

184
00:10:33,490 --> 00:10:38,030
I didn't expect you
to be on Instagram.

185
00:10:41,070 --> 00:10:43,840
Did I post anything
that gave away my location?

186
00:10:43,910 --> 00:10:44,910
No.

187
00:10:45,570 --> 00:10:46,940
That's why

188
00:10:47,740 --> 00:10:51,110
I searched every cheap internet cafe
you might stay at.

189
00:10:53,090 --> 00:10:54,450
Are you a stalker?

190
00:10:54,450 --> 00:10:55,950
This was the sixth one.

191
00:10:57,750 --> 00:11:00,750
I could have gone somewhere far.

192
00:11:00,750 --> 00:11:02,020
I knew you wouldn't.

193
00:11:04,030 --> 00:11:07,400
You're volunteering at the soup kitchen
next week, aren't you?

194
00:11:10,490 --> 00:11:14,400
I knew you wouldn't break a promise
and run off somewhere far.

195
00:11:17,470 --> 00:11:18,470
You...

196
00:11:20,410 --> 00:11:27,380
I finally understand
who Hasegawa Itsuki really is.

197
00:11:31,010 --> 00:11:32,010
I heard about it.

198
00:11:32,450 --> 00:11:33,690
Why you quit your job.

199
00:11:35,070 --> 00:11:36,790
Why didn't you tell me back then?

200
00:11:39,410 --> 00:11:41,370
Because I didn't think I needed to.

201
00:11:41,370 --> 00:11:42,710
Why not?

202
00:11:44,710 --> 00:11:45,800
Hey.

203
00:11:46,370 --> 00:11:51,010
If you had just told me,
maybe things would be different between us now.

204
00:11:56,730 --> 00:11:59,010
It's not because we didn't say it
that we ended up like this.

205
00:12:00,030 --> 00:12:02,070
It's because our relationship reached a point
where we couldn't be honest with each other.

206
00:12:02,080 --> 00:12:03,250
You know that, don't you?

207
00:12:06,690 --> 00:12:07,290
Hey!

208
00:12:07,290 --> 00:12:08,690
On your birthday,

209
00:12:20,740 --> 00:12:22,040
let's go to Enoshima.

210
00:12:29,080 --> 00:12:31,680
(Day 85) Why did you two
want to go to Enoshima last year?

211
00:12:31,680 --> 00:12:33,980
Oh, that was Itsuki's idea.

212
00:12:34,620 --> 00:12:36,650
We were planning a birthday trip,

213
00:12:36,650 --> 00:12:38,320
and he said he wanted to go to Enoshima.

214
00:12:39,510 --> 00:12:41,280
Hasegawa-san,
why did you want to go to Enoshima?

215
00:12:41,420 --> 00:12:42,420
Huh?

216
00:12:42,820 --> 00:12:44,460
Because I'd never been there.

217
00:12:44,630 --> 00:12:45,860
And it's pretty close by.

218
00:12:46,700 --> 00:12:49,200
- Just for that reason?
- Yeah.

219
00:12:52,730 --> 00:12:53,920
Kayano-san.

220
00:12:54,740 --> 00:12:55,800
I know.

221
00:12:55,880 --> 00:12:59,710
Next, we'll shoot the back view
for the final shot of Plan A.

222
00:12:59,780 --> 00:13:01,980
We'll wait for you here.

223
00:13:02,710 --> 00:13:03,880
Thank you.

224
00:13:03,880 --> 00:13:07,720
I should be the one thanking you.
Thank you for letting us keep filming.

225
00:13:07,720 --> 00:13:09,250
Oh, not at all.
Don't mention it.

226
00:13:11,700 --> 00:13:13,090
Let's go. It's freezing.

227
00:13:13,160 --> 00:13:13,860
Oh, right.

228
00:13:13,860 --> 00:13:14,590
We're off then.

229
00:13:37,250 --> 00:13:38,600
Are you sure about this?

230
00:13:38,600 --> 00:13:39,410
Yeah.

231
00:13:42,060 --> 00:13:45,190
We should be grateful
they let us film this much.

232
00:14:03,860 --> 00:14:04,860
Hey.

233
00:14:05,340 --> 00:14:07,010
They went this way, right?

234
00:14:07,640 --> 00:14:08,440
Yes.

235
00:14:09,340 --> 00:14:11,380
What is the "Lover's Bell"?

236
00:14:11,380 --> 00:14:12,580
What's over there?

237
00:14:13,340 --> 00:14:15,120
There's a bell and a fence.

238
00:14:15,120 --> 00:14:18,620
If you lock a padlock with your names on it
onto that fence,

239
00:14:19,580 --> 00:14:22,990
they say your love will last forever.

240
00:14:23,030 --> 00:14:23,960
What is that even supposed to mean?

241
00:14:23,960 --> 00:14:25,230
Is there any scientific basis for that?

242
00:14:25,680 --> 00:14:27,330
Does it really need a scientific basis?

243
00:14:27,500 --> 00:14:29,830
Because if it's not some ancient legend,

244
00:14:29,830 --> 00:14:31,030
isn't it just made up?

245
00:14:32,030 --> 00:14:33,640
How boring.

246
00:14:35,260 --> 00:14:38,070
I was actually hoping to go there with Shiho-san
after they get back.

247
00:14:39,010 --> 00:14:40,040
Why?

248
00:14:44,540 --> 00:14:48,680
Because I like you, Shiho-san.

249
00:14:51,340 --> 00:14:52,490
Oh.

250
00:14:56,390 --> 00:14:57,190
I'm serious.

251
00:14:57,230 --> 00:14:58,430
Sorry, not a chance.

252
00:14:58,630 --> 00:14:59,120
Huh?

253
00:14:59,120 --> 00:15:00,900
I don't feel that way about you at all.

254
00:15:01,400 --> 00:15:04,170
And I don't appreciate you saying
something like that while we're working.

255
00:15:04,580 --> 00:15:05,780
- Also...
- I get it.

256
00:15:07,280 --> 00:15:08,520
You don't have to say any more.

257
00:15:08,560 --> 00:15:09,600
I'm sorry.

258
00:15:18,240 --> 00:15:20,480
Let's pull ourselves together
and make this a great documentary.

259
00:15:21,220 --> 00:15:22,850
Of course.

260
00:15:24,620 --> 00:15:28,000
It's as spectacular as ever here.

261
00:15:30,730 --> 00:15:31,530
Hey.

262
00:15:31,960 --> 00:15:33,760
Where did we hang ours back then?

263
00:15:34,740 --> 00:15:35,840
I forgot.

264
00:15:36,560 --> 00:15:38,770
And it might have been taken down already.

265
00:15:39,760 --> 00:15:43,270
They probably clear them out regularly.
They wouldn't keep them for over a year.

266
00:15:46,140 --> 00:15:47,080
True.

267
00:15:47,480 --> 00:15:48,480
Yeah.

268
00:15:50,180 --> 00:15:53,820
But still...
I can't believe it's already been a year.

269
00:15:54,780 --> 00:15:55,780
Yeah.

270
00:15:58,560 --> 00:16:04,230
Back then, I never imagined
we'd end up like this.

271
00:16:05,820 --> 00:16:07,060
Of course not.

272
00:16:07,860 --> 00:16:10,630
If we knew it would turn out like this,
who would ever come to a place like this?

273
00:16:10,700 --> 00:16:11,700
Really?

274
00:16:13,640 --> 00:16:17,770
Maybe some couples whose relationships are failing
come here to try and fix things.

275
00:16:17,940 --> 00:16:20,540
So they come here to create a sense of commitment.

276
00:16:23,850 --> 00:16:28,020
The idea that if you go through the motions first,
the feelings will follow.

277
00:16:28,020 --> 00:16:30,490
It's actually quite common for people to think that way.

278
00:16:33,960 --> 00:16:35,190
I was like that.

279
00:16:38,480 --> 00:16:43,070
That's exactly why I agreed to do this documentary.

280
00:16:45,370 --> 00:16:51,470
Even though I said it was for the people supporting us
or for others going through the same pain,

281
00:16:52,170 --> 00:16:55,180
wrapping it up in all those pretty words,

282
00:16:56,350 --> 00:16:58,010
that wasn't my true motive.

283
00:17:02,460 --> 00:17:06,780
I thought if we acted like a model couple
in front of the camera,

284
00:17:07,980 --> 00:17:13,760
we would actually become one
behind the scenes too.

285
00:17:15,560 --> 00:17:16,570
Looking back, it was so shallow of me.

286
00:17:21,670 --> 00:17:23,510
Whether it was the partnership oath,

287
00:17:24,520 --> 00:17:26,410
taking you to my hometown,

288
00:17:27,980 --> 00:17:31,380
or coming here a year ago, it was all the same.

289
00:17:34,480 --> 00:17:36,550
Because I wanted us to be that kind of couple,

290
00:17:37,460 --> 00:17:39,520
I forced us to act like one.

291
00:17:44,140 --> 00:17:45,530
I always

292
00:17:47,500 --> 00:17:51,870
put my own ideals
ahead of your feelings.

293
00:17:57,200 --> 00:18:02,610
I never saw you
as an individual.

294
00:18:05,640 --> 00:18:07,480
I didn't respect that you have your own identity,

295
00:18:08,660 --> 00:18:09,890
your own will,

296
00:18:11,520 --> 00:18:13,560
and your own ideals.

297
00:18:18,060 --> 00:18:19,060
So,

298
00:18:21,360 --> 00:18:27,200
it's only natural
that you got tired of me.

299
00:18:33,210 --> 00:18:38,010
I was willing to force myself for your sake.

300
00:18:40,480 --> 00:18:41,380
Huh?

301
00:18:43,470 --> 00:18:45,490
That's why I came here with you last year.

302
00:18:46,990 --> 00:18:48,520
I rang the bell with you,

303
00:18:49,990 --> 00:18:51,760
and we hung the lock together.

304
00:18:53,450 --> 00:18:55,330
Going to your hometown,

305
00:18:56,470 --> 00:18:58,970
and doing the partnership oath, it was all for that reason.

306
00:19:00,430 --> 00:19:03,370
You said you didn't respect my identity,

307
00:19:04,110 --> 00:19:06,940
but wasn't it my own choice
not to reject you?

308
00:19:08,630 --> 00:19:10,680
Since I could force myself like that before,

309
00:19:11,770 --> 00:19:16,770
I could have kept forcing myself
for this documentary for your sake.

310
00:19:22,090 --> 00:19:25,560
I even thought, just like you did,

311
00:19:28,450 --> 00:19:34,070
I thought maybe this could be the chance
to repair our relationship.

312
00:19:39,110 --> 00:19:40,810
But I quickly realized...

313
00:19:42,790 --> 00:19:45,010
This wasn't forcing myself for you.

314
00:19:46,830 --> 00:19:51,830
I was compromising myself
for complete strangers.

315
00:19:54,290 --> 00:19:59,800
Of course, I don't think it's right

316
00:19:59,830 --> 00:20:02,030
for people like us to be discriminated against.

317
00:20:04,530 --> 00:20:05,530
It's just...

318
00:20:08,100 --> 00:20:09,140
Yeah...

319
00:20:10,810 --> 00:20:16,040
I don't want to compromise myself for them.

320
00:20:17,310 --> 00:20:20,620
Especially not for those who mock us
and use our interview videos for entertainment.

321
00:20:20,620 --> 00:20:21,680
That's out of the question.

322
00:20:23,830 --> 00:20:28,830
But you made me feel like nothing else mattered,

323
00:20:30,170 --> 00:20:33,060
as long as we made a good documentary.

324
00:20:35,300 --> 00:20:37,500
That created a huge conflict inside me.

325
00:20:40,840 --> 00:20:42,270
I slowly realized

326
00:20:43,440 --> 00:20:46,610
I didn't even want to force myself for you anymore.

327
00:20:50,850 --> 00:20:52,850
Once the filming actually started,

328
00:20:53,450 --> 00:20:55,420
that feeling grew even stronger.

329
00:20:56,190 --> 00:21:00,660
It finally boiled over,
leading to where we are today.

330
00:21:05,790 --> 00:21:06,930
But still...

331
00:21:08,030 --> 00:21:10,570
I guess since I agreed to do it in the first place,

332
00:21:11,730 --> 00:21:14,070
I should have talked things through with you properly.

333
00:21:14,940 --> 00:21:16,540
So in the end,

334
00:21:17,670 --> 00:21:20,510
I didn't treat you
as an individual either.

335
00:21:22,090 --> 00:21:24,010
We're actually quite similar in that way.

336
00:21:25,350 --> 00:21:28,220
If we were compatible,
maybe we would have been a model couple.

337
00:21:29,590 --> 00:21:31,350
Too bad we're not.

338
00:21:44,510 --> 00:21:45,500
Hey.

339
00:21:47,910 --> 00:21:49,410
All these padlocks here...

340
00:21:52,110 --> 00:21:53,910
Even though there's an incredible number of them,

341
00:21:56,070 --> 00:21:57,880
I doubt everyone who hung them

342
00:21:58,980 --> 00:22:01,750
ended up happy.

343
00:22:04,870 --> 00:22:08,720
They rang the bell, hung the lock,

344
00:22:10,710 --> 00:22:14,300
and then broke up six months later, three months later,

345
00:22:15,050 --> 00:22:20,040
or maybe even that very night.
I'm sure there are plenty of couples like that.

346
00:22:22,130 --> 00:22:24,040
But that's just how things normally go.

347
00:22:26,350 --> 00:22:27,510
So,

348
00:22:29,610 --> 00:22:33,120
for an ordinary couple like us,

349
00:22:34,650 --> 00:22:36,320
it's only natural for this to happen.

350
00:23:03,350 --> 00:23:04,350
Itsuki.

351
00:23:23,570 --> 00:23:25,200
Let's break up.

352
00:23:35,710 --> 00:23:36,780
Yeah.

353
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:46,300
(Preview of the Final Episode)

354
00:23:46,330 --> 00:23:48,110
We'll leave it in your hands then.

355
00:23:48,110 --> 00:23:51,470
When we first started living together,
I probably thought that was endearing too.

356
00:23:51,550 --> 00:23:53,150
Ultimately, it's just easier that way.

357
00:23:53,170 --> 00:23:54,800
Because our feelings never truly aligned.

358
00:23:54,830 --> 00:23:56,120
We could never make it work, no matter what.

359
00:23:56,170 --> 00:23:57,430
It's not because we hate each other.

360
00:23:57,470 --> 00:23:58,570
I just...

361
00:23:59,090 --> 00:23:59,990
I...
